  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 30.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he charged them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "επετίμησεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") - a strong word, implying almost rebuke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he strictly charged them - that they should tell no man of him",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "he strictly charged them - ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "that they should tell no man of him",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Why was this? There were many reasons for this reticence. The state of parties in Palestine was most inexpedient for such a disclosure at that time. Those who were favorable to his cause would have wanted at once to take him by force and make him a king. In fact, some of them made no secret of their intentions (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 6:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Those, on the other hand, who were opposed to him were only watching their opportunity to destroy him. Moreover, his own disciples had yet many things to learn; and besides all this, faith in his Godhead would be easier when his death should have been followed by his glorious resurrection and ascension. Mark 8:30",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
